@node hints "A Little Trick For Viewing Files"
@{line}
    @{fg shine}@{b}How to get the best out of DirScanner@{ub}@{fg text}@{line}
    @{i}from Andreas Mixich@{ui}@{line}

    @{b}DirScanner@{ub} offers one program to view the files it found.
However, most probably  the  filetypes can be very different from datatypes you have,
or you just prefer showing pictures with another program,  than, let's say,  @{b}MultiView@{ub}.
You're in trouble ! What can you do ? You could write yourself an ARexx script,
doing some extra filetype-recognition,  which then  launches  your  favourite  viewer for that specific filetype. But
maybe you can not program ARexx ? Or just don't want to ?@{par}
@{line}
In this case you should have a look at Aminet. Aminet holds several such utilities, which allow viewing of files depending on their type.
So far, one of the most powerful is contained in Action.lha. It relies on the fileid.library but allows additional, user-specific definitions, such as MIME Types.
In a prefs-file you define which viewer you want for a specific filetype. You also can group filetypes to use the same viewer and set up aliases.@{par}
At the end, you just have to deal with three commands: View, Edit, Indentify, each one has its own configuration. Form now on you use the Edit command for gfx, binaries, ASCII or anything else. The right editor will be invoked. That easy. That simple.
You might also have a look at any of the other tools at Aminet, however, this one is very powerful.
@endnode
